Based on the provided evidence, option A correctly identifies that thiamine deficiency decreases cellular metabolism primarily because thiamine is a coenzyme for pyruvate dehydrogenase and alpha-ketoglutarate dehydrogenases, which play crucial roles in converting pyruvate to acetyl-CoA and facilitating the entry of carbon atoms into the TCA cycle. This disruption leads to inefficient energy production, causing lactic acid buildup and ultimately impacting overall cellular function. Other options focus on different aspects of thiamine action or side effects unrelated to immediate cellular metabolism inhibition caused by thiamine deficiency. Therefore, I agree with Option A. \boxed{A}
